tical background to modern slavery, the literary tradition of the slave narrative, and a variety of ways we can all help end slavery today.Halting the contemporary slave trade is one of the great human-rights issues of our time. But just as slavery is not over, neither is the will to achieve freedom, "plead" the cause of liberation, and advocate abolition. Putting the slave's voice back at the heart of the abolitionist movement, To Plead Our Own Cause gives occasion for both action and hope.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aForced laborvCase studies. 0aHuman traffickingvCase studies. 0aProstitutionvCase studies. 0aSlaveryvCase studies. 0aSlaveryxHistoryy21st century. 0aSlavesvBiography. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aSlavery Studies. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Slavery.2bisacsh1 aBales, Kevin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTrodd, Zoe, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z97831105361570 cprintz978080144573640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801458323423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801458323/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK